“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to come in like Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says joining NATO would provide the much-needed investment for Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is over 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80 percent of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published Monday by the Policy Research Institute, it was assured that between 30 and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, which is less than the required participation.
