"The sea belongs to us": a landlocked Bolivia has the hope that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
The sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings wave navy blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to sail again the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia expects a decision by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the ruling of the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country, hoping that the Hague court will vote in favour of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who wages a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has a lot to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN agency has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the decision of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have hampered it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
In addition, he suggested that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, would use the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind.”
