North Korea says "there's no chance" of unilateral disarmament first if they don't have confidence
On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister informed the United Nations that continued sanctions deepened his distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would give up nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the international body’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities, and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we do not receive any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence with regard to our national security, and under those circumstances, there is no possibility that we will first disarm unilaterally.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints over Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not simply reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons sooner.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose coercively, including by objecting to a declaration of termination of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, hymnally announced by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea’s leader, over the past five months, and added: “If South Korea had been the interested party in denuclearization rather than the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward U.S. soil after “evil President” Trump, on a suicidal mission, called Kim “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing disarmament, but said much remains to be done and that sanctions needed to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no set deadline for this: “We can take two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its advances.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we realize definitive and fully verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying advances had taken place, but a few hours later, North Korea denounced his "requirements were those of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had informed him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take a Course on How to Rest Enough
Thanks to a new course taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep longer in an attempt to fight against the growing macho culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of its kind in the US.
Her motivation to launch the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked me why she just learned about this now, in her senior year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a routine for going to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it’s not going to change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
He claimed that the culture of pride in “spending the night on a wake” still exists, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure students face meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physics biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the entire campus.
He hopes the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
