Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now, a page of the Almanac section of the "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, today 136 years ago, and CONTANTING... the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that culminated with the device known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter, which has since been a pillar of science, has also become a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "The Bells of Coronado," with actors Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in the seemingly incompatible roles of cowboy scientists:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
By putting on your headphones, you can hear the effect of the waves emitted by the radioactivity of the minerals.”
Evans: "It's like a radio!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, when he was about to turn 63.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" malignant cells and kill them.
As part of treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
