The inventor of the World Wide Web considers launching a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that tries to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest project in the tech legend, a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to “dominate the world.”
“It has to be now,” he said of the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology so that users can create their own "online personal data storage" or a POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available in one browser and at the same time.
One thing that is unique in the storage of personal data online is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what type of information.
The company calls it “personal training through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to incorporate resources, processes and skills needed for Solid to reach everyone.
At the moment, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the staffed developers who were hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world could build their own decentralized apps with the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not a radical change will be introduced where all their business models are completely modified overnight.
“We’re not going to ask for permission.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that “its mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web created on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the debate on net neutrality.
Despite even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this upcoming era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
