This new research, which has been conducted in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their hunt for food.
Everything that is found is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as Daubenton’s coastal bat and long-eared browns from the Inverewe Gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research with portable detectors.
