Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticidal papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not really blind,
but because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the field, who are dedicated to conducting regular surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated the first and only reserve dedicated to Scotland’s bats in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says it’s the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave, we have a fantastic bat area," he said.
“We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as a breeding colony can be involuntarily destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean annihilating an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or harass them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish official in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
