Syria ready for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and seeks help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has already been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country were improving.
"The situation on the ground is today more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in an attempt to restore normality.
All conditions are already in place for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted the insurgency.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the North American team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, just outside Paris (France).
The United States now has six consecutive losses on European soil since last winning a Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe regained the crown when the team of the Danish captain Thomas Bjorn achieved the 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight for most of the tournament, threw his starting point into the water in hole 16 par 3, thus admitting his defeat to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari stood out in all his rounds, becoming one of the four players who have never achieved a 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth fell defeated by 5 and 4 against the player with the lowest standings of the European team, the Dane Thorbjørn Olesen.
World No. 1 player Dustin Johnson fell 2-1 to Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, a veteran who already has eight Ryder Cups, became the European with the most tournament wins of all time, with 25.5 points in his career.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help it.
It's been a very hard year.
I am totally grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I am very, very happy that I was able to recover the cup.
It’s an achievement of the whole team and I’m very happy to have been able to help,” said a thrilled Garcia following the European team’s victory.
Now he passes the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who already beat U.S. golf legend Tiger Woods 2-1 on Sunday in a singles match.
"I feel an incredible pride in beating Tiger Woods, as I've grown up watching this man," said 23-year-old golfer John Rahm.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 in his Ryder Cup career.
This is a strange statistic for one of the best players of all time, who has won 14 great titles, leaving only behind Jack Nicklaus.
The American team had to fight all weekend to find the streets, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team’s disappointing performance: “I’m very proud of these guys, they’ve never stopped fighting.
There was a moment this morning when we warmed up the situation in Europe.
But we ruined it.
I want to congratulate Thomas.
He's a great captain.
Their 12 players have made a very good game.
We will regroup, meet with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Committee, and move on.
I love these 12 guys very much and I am proud to be their captain.
Now it's up to us to bow our heads.
They've overtaken us."
Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
Red tide flowering extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but on fewer sites compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, low-to-high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coast, background to elevated concentrations in Manatee County, background to elevated concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, background to mid-level concentrations in Charlotte County, background to elevated concentrations in Leicester County, and background to elevated concentrations in Leicester County.
Respiratory irritation problems are still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation problems in northwest Florida during the past week.
